<div id="review_1218135018" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1218135018" />
    <a title="Cindy S" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30184125-cindy-s"><img alt="Cindy S" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1422891006p2/30184125.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1218135018?book_show_action=true">Mar 04, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cindy S" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cindy S" href="/user/show/30184125-cindy-s">Cindy S</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780988661004" href="/book/show/17914159-let-it-be">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1218135018" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14176445096561837747">Bill and Michelle Jansen were Texans, and so were their children, Joseph and Pam. Their family was similar to many other families, in that it was torn apart by divorce. Pam was 13 and Joseph was 10 when he heard their mother and father talking in the other room, and the bluntness of his father&apos;s voice. It was then, that his father told him the story of the mockingbird and how it returned to its cage after being released because it turned out that it was too hard to live outside that cage. And it</span>
  <span id="freeText14176445096561837747" style="display:none">Bill and Michelle Jansen were Texans, and so were their children, Joseph and Pam. Their family was similar to many other families, in that it was torn apart by divorce. Pam was 13 and Joseph was 10 when he heard their mother and father talking in the other room, and the bluntness of his father's voice. It was then, that his father told him the story of the mockingbird and how it returned to its cage after being released because it turned out that it was too hard to live outside that cage. And it was then, that his mother fell in love once again with the songs of the Beatles. And it was also during this period that Joseph almost killed a man....<br /><br />This story is about heartache, about families that are caught in the twisting dust cloud of divorce, and the pain of verbal and physical abuse. It's about a boy who dreams of comets, missions to Mars, black holes in space, and having his family go back to the way it was when they were all together. It's about a mother who just wants to be in charge of her life and provide for her children in a calm, loving environment. It's about a man that has no boundaries when it comes to getting his family back.<br /><br />Each chapter is titled after one of the songs from the Beatles 1970 album "Let it be". I am not sure if any of the characters felt the possible meaning of that song, not to worry because everything will work out the way it should, but sadly, their story doesn't portray that.<br /><br />Some chapters were written from Joseph's perspective, one is from Pam's, some are Michelle's, which at times could be a little confusing. However, it is well written, and reflects the all too often emotional entanglement of dissolving families that involve abuse.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14176445096561837747" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


